, the work of a Northern free black, also provides a working-class portrait of New England farm life, removed from the frontier that dominates accounts of American agrarian life. Telegraphy - which transformed transatlantic relations in the middle of the century- was used by spiritualists as a metaphor for the ways in which communications from the other world could be understood. The story of the Bolton Whitman Fellowship is discussed. Beside Sarah Orne Jewett's desk was a small copy of the well-known Raeburn portrait of Sir Walter Scott. Henry James and George Eliot shared a transatlantic literary network which embodied an easy flow of mutual interest and appreciation between their two milieux. In her autobiography, Gertrude Stein assigns to her lifelong companion the repeated comment that she has met three geniuses in her life: Stein, Picasso, and Alfred North Whitehead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAlfred North Whitehead.  aBolton Whitman Fellowship.  aBritain's foreign policy.  aBritish governments.  aGeorge Eliot.  aGertrude Stein.  aHarriet Beecher Stowe.  aHenry James.  aHighland Clearances.  aMark Twain.  aNew England farm life.  aPicasso.  aSarah Orne Jewett.  aWalter Scott.  ahegemonic US.  apost-Second World War British governments.  atransatlantic literary network.  aworking-class portrait.1 aBeer, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeer, Janet, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBennett, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennett, Bridget, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat